segments.text: What was it?
Where was it?
What was in it?
Bonfire.
My outfit, first two years I was there, was one of the stacking units.
Only one time do I ever remember going out to the cutting fields to do any cutting of trees.
But they'd bring them in to where the bonfire was stacked.
They'd bring them into the bonfire area.
And our outfit was one of about three or so that was responsible for lifting the logs up and putting them on the stack.
And it was right there just south of Duncan Hall.
And I look now at how they do all that, take a whole year to do it, and we do it on about two weekends, it seems like.
And it was huge, huge.
The bonfire was much taller, I think.
I'm not sure, it's probably bigger around in circumference now, but ours went up a lot taller, I believe.
And I developed such a,
resistance to it from freshman and sophomore years that your junior and senior year you didn't have to work on it.
I didn't.
But it was an experience.
Let's see.
Do you have any nostalgic memory of when you got your senior ring?
Was that a special?
Yeah.
As I remember, I qualified for mine maybe a little bit early.
But I qualified for it when I was a junior.
But I didn't want to wear it because I was afraid seniors would get on me.
But that was the one thing that I really wanted to have.
In fact, I can still remember, I think, getting my senior ring was more important to me than getting senior boots in the Corps.
Did you or any of your buddies celebrate in any way when you got your ring?
No, they have that tradition now where they go dunk their ring or something like that and drink a pitcher of beer.
No, I don't.
That wasn't done in your era?
No.
Oh, okay.
At least, if it was, I certainly didn't know that.
Because one of our children was telling me about that, and they've heard stories of people trying to
to drink and almost swallow the ring.
I bet that's right.
No, I think the way they do it now is they dunk the ring and then you have to drink the pitcher of beer and get it out.
No, there wasn't anything like that.
Senior boots, did you have new ones?
I had new ones.
Made at Hollick's.
What did they cost, do you remember?
I don't.
I remember I saved up money and bought them.
Did you keep them or pass?
No, I've kept them.
I've kept them.
And I don't really have any, I didn't have any intentions.
Some people wanted to make lamps and all that stuff.
I probably still got them at home somewhere.
Let's see.
Okay, we're getting close to the end.
What are the...
ingredients, what makes up, what contributes to Aggie spirit?
That's a hard one to understand.
You know, it's a funny thing.
I think that what made A&M unique initially was
was the isolation, the shared bad experiences.
And out of that came some good things.
And I think that that bred a camaraderie that
Maybe it's not being recreated today the same way, but it created these traditions.
But now the traditions are honored because they're traditions, but back then it was just the way of life.
It was the way things were done.
And I think that's what it was.
I think the groups back in the 30s and 40s, it was deprivation.
Most of those guys didn't have any money.
And they went to A&M to get skills so they could make a living.
By the time I was there, it had become more of an academic place.
And even the students who were civilian students came there.
It was still isolated.
It wasn't that they had it totally easy.
It wasn't nearly like it is now.
They came there and were away from everything.
And I really think that there was a closer bond between civilian students and people in the Corps than people might imagine that there was.
But I think that's what it was, a sense of when people look back, I knew that A&M had changed when I used to hear people with kids who were at A&M tell me, oh, they're down there, they love it.
Because I can remember my freshman year, I never would have used the words I love it to describe it.
What qualities does an Aggie have?
You know, I alluded earlier to the belief that one of the benefits of the Corps was the leveling factor.
That it made you successful based on what you were and not what you had.
And I think there's always been, in a sense, that aspect of A&M.
That it valued people for merit and for accomplishment.
regardless of bank account or color of their skin or anything like that.
I would like to think that it would still be that way, but I think it's probably changed some because of the size and everything.
It's a very, well, anybody who thinks they can define the Aggie spirit, it's so elusive because you can't duplicate it.
If you try to duplicate it, then you say, well, tell us what's important.
And we'll go, hey, you can't make it.
It's caused by a lot of people who've cared about that place and put that back into the school.
And when people talk about, when people talk now in society about giving back, you won't find any better example of people giving back than what has been given back to that school by former students.
And I hope that the students now have a sense, some sense of that.
Alright, this is the last question that has some, what did it mean to you that you attended A&M?
How did it affect your life?
What feelings do you have in your heart for A&M now?
What did it mean to you that you went to A&M and said somewhere else?
That's a hard question for me to answer because I don't have anything to compare it with.
So in a sense, you can't say, well, it changed my life this way.
I know that it was good in that, first of all, it gave me...
a group of people with good reputations to attach my name to.
And then when I was out of school, it gave me some roots, an identity.
I could identify with it.
Because even if I didn't identify with A&M, everybody else identifies you with A&M.
And then it gave me people, when I came back to this town, it gave me people who have commonality of shared experiences, even at different times.
And a lot of my best friends around here went to India, and we maintained some of those loyalties.
So it's been extremely helpful to me in providing that continuous identity.
continuous contact with people that I was in school with.
And in that sense, that's the main thing, I think.
I'm not sure I've expressed it very well.
What feelings do you have in your heart for A&M today?
Well, if you ask my family, they'd probably say that it's more important to me than my family, but it's not.
I just want to see it continue to thrive and prosper and do well and become better in every respect.
A lot of my friends want to see the Corps continue.
That's fine.
I want to see it do well in everything it does academically, athletically, reputation, bringing in the best students.
I want to see it be excellent in every regard.
So that's just, I don't know if that expresses it very well.
Is there anything we haven't talked about that we should have?
I don't know.
I feel like I'm drained.
I had thought about a lot of this stuff.
What you're telling me then, there's not something about, well, hey, I was just waiting for him to get to this, that, or the other.
I don't think so.
I've tried to ask you similar questions that I have to anyone else.
So let's quit with that.
